  "prompt": "My Windows 8.1 system is taking unusually long time to start / boot on Lenovo PC .Could there be any solutions?",
  "response": "If your Windows 8.1 system is taking an unusually long time to boot on your Lenovo PC, there are several potential solutions you can try to resolve the issue:\n\n1. **Disable Startup Programs**:\n   Many programs are set to start with Windows automatically, which can slow down the boot process.\n   - Press `Ctrl + Shift + Esc` to open Task Manager.\n   - Go to the `Startup` tab.\n   - Disable non-essential programs by right-clicking and selecting `Disable`.\n\n2. **Update Drivers**:\n   Ensure that all your drivers are up to date, especially the ones related to the chipset, graphics, and storage.\n   - Visit the Lenovo website, navigate to the support section, and download the latest drivers for your model.\n   - You can also use Device Manager (`Win + X` > Device Manager) to update drivers.\n\n3. **Check for Windows Updates**:\n   Make sure your system has all the latest Windows updates and patches.\n   - Go to `Settings` > `Update & Security` > `Windows Update` and check for updates.\n\n4. **Clean Up Disk**:\n   Free up disk space and clean up your system to improve performance:\n   - Use Disk Cleanup (`Win + S`, search for Disk Cleanup) to remove temporary files.\n   - Consider using a tool like CCleaner to clean up junk files and fix registry issues.\n\n5. **Run System Maintenance Tasks**:\n   - Open `Control Panel`, go to `System and Security`, and select `Administrative Tools`.\n   - Run `Disk Defragmenter` to optimize disk performance.\n   - Use `System File Checker` to repair corrupted files (`sfc /scannow` from Command Prompt with admin rights).\n\n6. **Check for Malware**:\n   Malware can significantly slow down your system.\n   - Run a full system scan using Windows Defender or your preferred antivirus program.\n\n7. **Check Hardware**:\n   Ensure that there are no hardware issues affecting performance.\n   - Inspect and test your hard drive for errors. Use tools like `chkdsk` (`chkdsk /f` from Command Prompt with admin rights).\n   - If the hard drive is old or failing, consider upgrading to an SSD which can significantly improve boot times.\n\n8. **Adjust Virtual Memory**:\n   Ensure that your virtual memory settings are appropriate.\n   - Go to `Control Panel` > `System and Security` > `System` > `Advanced System Settings` > `Settings under Performance`.\n   - In the `Advanced` tab, under `Virtual Memory`, click `Change` and adjust the settings if necessary.\n\n9. **Last Resort: Reinstall Windows**:\n   If none of the above solutions work, consider reinstalling Windows. Make sure to back up your data first.\n   - Use the built-in recovery options to restore your PC to its factory settings or perform a fresh installation.\n\nBy following these steps, you should be able to identify and resolve the issue causing slow boot times on your Lenovo PC running Windows 8.1.",
